06079nam a22007935i 9780292735422DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212012txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927354227 a10.7560/7287762doi  a(DE-B1597)586776  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aDG70.M52 -- L36 2012eb 7aSOC0030002bisacsh04a937/.7731 aLapadula, Erminia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Chora of Metaponto 4 :bThe Late Roman Farmhouse at San Biagio /cErminia Lapadula. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2012  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- t1. The Farmhouse at San Biagio and the Agricultural Landscape of Basilicata in the Roman Period -- t2. The Excavation and Structures -- tThe Setting -- tThe 1980 Excavation The Site -- tRe-evaluation of the Site’s Occupation -- tBuilding Materials -- tInterpretation of the Roman Structure Carter’s 1980 Interpretation -- tVirtual Archaeology: A Proposed Reconstruction -- t3. The Materials: Prehistoric through the Roman Republican Period -- tIntroduction -- tPottery and Other Neolithic Artifacts -- tBlack Gloss and Grey Ware -- tBanded Ware, Miniatures, and Plain Ware -- tCooking Ware -- tTransport Amphorae -- tArchitectural Terracottas -- tCoroplastic -- tLoom Weights -- t4. The Materials: The Roman Imperial Period -- t5. Furnishings, Utilitarian Artifacts, and Coins -- tIntroduction -- tPersonal Artifacts -- tHousehold Instruments -- tSpinning, Weaving, and Sewing -- tLamps -- tTools for Fire-lighting, Carpentry, and Woodworking -- tThe Repair of Dolia -- tWindow Glass -- tCoins -- t6. Archaeozoology, Archaeometry, and Ceramic Analysis -- tThe Archaeozoological Data -- tA Goat Skeleton from the Roman Period -- tArchaeometric Analyses of Metal, Glass, and Plaster -- tMicroscopy of Selected Pottery Fabrics -- t7. Conclusions -- tReference Materials0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume in the Institute of Classical Archaeology's series on rural settlements in the countryside (chora) of Metaponto presents the excavation of the Late Roman farmhouse at San Biagio. Located near the site of an earlier Greek sanctuary, this modest but well-appointed structure was an unexpected find from a period generally marked by large landholdings and monumental villas. Description of earlier periods of occupation (Neolithic and Greek) is followed by a detailed discussion of the farmhouse itself and its historical and socioeconomic context. The catalogs and analyses of finds include impressive deposits of coins from the late third and early fourth centuries AD. Use of virtual reality CAD software has yielded a deeper understanding of the architectural structure and its reconstruction. A remarkable feature is the small bath complex, with its examples of window glass. This study reveals the existence of a small but viable rural social and economic entity and alternative to the traditional image of crisis and decline during the Late Imperial period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh1 aBartosiewicz, László, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalvaruso, Oda Teresa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCavallo, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColeman Carter, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDi Tursi, Antonietta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aD’Annibale, Cesare, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFox